HEADWORD: Nummulary
<hw>Num"mu*la*ry</hw>
<pr>(?)</pr>, }</mhw> <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>nummularius</ets>, fr.
<ets>nummulus</ets>, dim. of <ets>nummus</ets> a coin: cf. F.
<ets>nummulaire</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to coin or money; pecuniary;
<as>as, the <ex>nummulary</ex> talent</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Pathol.)</fld> <def>Having the appearance or form
of a coin.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Nummular</xex> sputa.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Sir T.
Watson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Nummulation</ent>⟦br⟧
